<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-integration-by-parts-and-change-of-variables"
  xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Integration by Parts and Change of Variables</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      The Fundamental Theorem of Calculus turns differentiation rules into
      integration formulas. Two of the most useful are integration by parts,
      which comes from the product rule, and change of variables, which comes
      from the chain rule.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-integration-by-parts">
    <title>Integration by Parts</title>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-integration-by-parts">
      <title>Integration by Parts</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>F</m> and <m>G</m> are differentiable on <m>[a,b]</m>
          and that <m>F'</m> and <m>G'</m> are both integrable on
          <m>[a,b]</m>. Then
          <me>
            \int_a^b F(x)G'(x)\,dx
            =
            F(b)G(b)-F(a)G(a)-\int_a^b F'(x)G(x)\,dx.
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Since differentiability implies continuity, both <m>F</m> and
          <m>G</m> are continuous on <m>[a,b]</m>. Hence
          <xref ref="thm-continuous-function-integrable" text="title"/>
          shows that <m>F,G \in R[a,b]</m>. Because <m>F'</m> and <m>G'</m>
          are integrable by assumption, <xref
          ref="prop-product-of-integrable-functions"/> implies that
          <m>F'G</m> and <m>FG'</m> are integrable.
        </p>

        <p>
          By the product rule
          (<xref ref="prop-derivative-sum-product-rules"/>),
          <me>
            (FG)'=F'G+FG'.
          </me>
          Therefore <m>(FG)'</m> is integrable, by part (1) of
          <xref ref="thm-basic-properties-riemann-integral" text="title"/>.
          Applying <xref ref="thm-ftc-first-form" text="title"/> to
          <m>FG</m>, we get
          <me>
            F(b)G(b)-F(a)G(a)
            =
            \int_a^b (FG)'(x)\,dx
            =
            \int_a^b F'(x)G(x)\,dx + \int_a^b F(x)G'(x)\,dx.
          </me>
          Rearranging yields the formula.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-change-of-variables">
    <title>Change of Variables</title>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-change-of-variables">
      <title>Change of Variables</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>\varphi \in C^1[a,b]</m>, and let <m>f</m> be continuous on
          <m>\varphi([a,b])</m>. Then
          <me>
            \int_a^b f(\varphi(x))\varphi'(x)\,dx
            =
            \int_{\varphi(a)}^{\varphi(b)} f(u)\,du.
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Since <m>f</m> is continuous on <m>\varphi([a,b])</m>, the second
          form of the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus
          (<xref ref="thm-ftc-second-form"/>) gives a function
          <me>
            U(y)=\int_{\varphi(a)}^{y} f(u)\,du
            \qquad (y \in \varphi([a,b]))
          </me>
          such that <m>U'(y)=f(y)</m> for every <m>y \in \varphi([a,b])</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Define <m>H(x)=U(\varphi(x))</m> on <m>[a,b]</m>. By the chain rule,
          <me>
            H'(x)=U'(\varphi(x))\varphi'(x)=f(\varphi(x))\varphi'(x).
          </me>
          Because <m>\varphi</m> and <m>\varphi'</m> are continuous on
          <m>[a,b]</m>, and <m>f</m> is continuous on <m>\varphi([a,b])</m>,
          the function <m>f \circ \varphi</m> is continuous on <m>[a,b]</m>.
          Hence <m>H'</m> is continuous, in particular integrable, on
          <m>[a,b]</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Applying <xref ref="thm-ftc-first-form" text="title"/> to <m>H</m>,
          we obtain
          <me>
            \int_a^b f(\varphi(x))\varphi'(x)\,dx
            =
            \int_a^b H'(x)\,dx
            =
            H(b)-H(a)
            =
            U(\varphi(b))-U(\varphi(a)).
          </me>
          Since <m>U(\varphi(a))=0</m>, the right-hand side is
          <me>
            \int_{\varphi(a)}^{\varphi(b)} f(u)\,du.
          </me>
          This proves the formula.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>

    <example xml:id="eg-change-of-variables-x-over-one-plus-xsq">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider
          <me>
            \int_{-1}^{2} \frac{x}{1+x^2}\,dx.
          </me>
          Let <m>\varphi(x)=1+x^2</m> and <m>f(u)=1/(2u)</m>. Then
          <me>
            \varphi'(x)=2x
            \qquad\text{and}\qquad
            f(\varphi(x))\varphi'(x)
            =
            \frac{1}{2(1+x^2)}\cdot 2x
            =
            \frac{x}{1+x^2}.
          </me>
          Therefore the change-of-variables theorem gives
          <me>
            \int_{-1}^{2} \frac{x}{1+x^2}\,dx
            =
            \int_{2}^{5} \frac{1}{2u}\,du
            =
            \frac12 \ln\frac{5}{2}.
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </subsection>
</section>
